<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Sterling put firmly in spotlight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A WAVE of overnight buying put sterling firmly in the spotlight on currency
markets yesterday, writes James Blitz.
Having closed at DM2.9140 the previous night, the currency opened in London
at DM2.9310 yesterday and closed at DM2.9308. It also strengthened against a
lifeless dollar, finishing at Dollars 1.7630, compared with Dollars 1.7480
previously. In New York it ended at Dollars 1.7625.
By the end of the day, sterling had clambered above the French franc in the
ERM grid for the first time since it joined the system in October 1990,
reaching its best levels for nearly a year.
Traders said overnight buying of sterling, estimated to be around Pounds
400m, came from a number of sources, including Singapore and another Far
East Asian state.
One trader explained the pound's popularity as a reaction to better news
about the UK economic recovery. He also said that foreign investors had been
short in sterling assets. There were claims, too, that investors were
gambling on the possibility that sterling would soon enter the narrow band
of the EMS.
By contrast, the D-Mark had a bad day, ending weaker against most
currencies. According to Mr Julian Simmonds of Citibank, uncertainty about
the German currency may be linked to the run-up to this weekend's G7 meeting
in Washington. 'There is a feeling that the G7 will push for lower interest
rates in Germany to promote growth throughout Europe,' he said. 'That is why
the Mark is being sold.'
The D-Mark dropped to its lowest level for a year against the French franc,
closing at FFr3.3773 from FFr3.3795. Fears of a strike by German public
sector workers also unsettled the currency.
The French unit was at its highest level in a year against the D-Mark on a
combination of corporate demand and investor confidence that the government
of Mr Pierre Beregovoy, the French prime minister, will keep the French
franc strong.
In late Asian trading, the dollar ended steady against the yen and the
D-Mark on continued bullish sentiment. Earlier it reached a high of Y134.58,
after which strong resistance prompted dealers to take profits. The dollar
closed in Tokyo at Y134.25 and DM1.6701.
In London, the US currency continued to sag, slipping from DM1.6700 to
DM1.6635. Traders said operators saw no reason to buy dollars until they
have fresh information on the state of the US economy. The next pointers are
due today with the publication of US durable goods orders for March, and
latest weekly jobless claims.
In the US, the dollar was softer against most currencies at midday after
swaying delicately in narrow trading bands throughout the morning. The US
unit finished New York trading at Y134.20/27 and DM1.6620/25.
</TEXT>
