<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / International Company News: Ralston may spin off baking
subsidiary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RALSTON Purina, the consumer products company which last week acquired the
UK Ever Ready battery business from Hanson for Dollars 227m, announced
yesterday it is considering the spin-off of its baking subsidiary to
shareholders.
The subsidiary, Continental Baking Company, claims to be the nation's
largest wholesale baker of fresh delivered bread and sweet baked goods, and
makes about 250,000 direct sales calls and deliveries each day. Its brands
include the 'Wonder' bread products and 'Twinkies' cupcakes.
The bakery business was bought by Ralston in 1984 from ITT, the big
conglomerate. In the year to end-September, it had sales of around Dollars
1.97bn, and total assets of around Dollars 765m. Its operating profit was
around Dollars 140m, after environmental and restructuring charges of
Dollars 17m.
The 'demerger' plan will be reviewed by directors of Ralston, based in St
Louis, on May 28. Even if it is approved, tax clearances and other technical
matters will take sometime to resolve, and the transaction would probably
not take place for another nine to 12 months.
However, Ralston said the demerger, if completed, would probably involve a
dividend of up to Dollars 600m being paid from Continental Baking Company to
Ralston. The stock market immediately marked Ralston shares Dollars 1 1/4
higher, at Dollars 48 3/4 , while Standard &amp; Poor's, the US rating agency,
affirmed its debt ratings.
Ralston's proposed moves come amid a modest spate of demergers in the US -
ranging from Union Carbide, with its industrial gases business, to Dial
Corporation with its financial services division.
Ralston said the aim of the move was 'to enhance shareholder value by
focusing more specifically on its other core businesses'. The bakery market
in the US - in common with the UK - is a mature industry, with total sales
of Dollars 7.4bn and static volumes in 1991. Continental saw lower volumes
in 1991, although higher margins meant operating profit was flat.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
