<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / ICI to sell fibres unit to Du Pont
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPERIAL Chemical Industries, the British chemicals group, plans today to
announce the sale of its fibres operations to Du Pont of the US. It is
calling press conferences in London and Teesside to announce the deal.
If ICI sells Du Pont its entire fibres operations, the deal would have to be
cleared by the European Commission. The combined operations would have 55
per cent of the European market for staple fibres, used in carpets and
clothing, and more than 30 per cent of the filament market.
Analysts estimate the businesses, which had a turnover of about Pounds 675m
in 1990, the last year the company published their results independently,
could be worth as much as Pounds 350m. The operations are, however,
unprofitable.
Sir Denys Henderson, chairman, has said in the past that he no longer saw
fibres as one of its core businesses. He said he planned to develop
businesses which operated on a global basis or were highly profitable. The
fibres operations meet neither criterion. Their sales are concentrated in
Europe and the businesses do not have a sustained record of profitability.
ICI is facing chronic overcapacity and keen competition from Asia, problems
shared by all European and North American fibres manufacturers, said Mr
Stuart Wamsley, editor of Focus on Chemicals, an industry newsletter.
Other fibres groups have already reacted to the poor market. In 1990,
Courtaulds, the UK specialty chemicals group, set up two joint ventures for
its acrylic fibres operations and acetate yarn business. Last month
Rhone-Poulenc of France and Snia of Italy merged their staple fibre and
polyamide carpet yarn operations.
ICI appeared to have turned its fibres operations around during the late
1980s by exiting the polyester business and concentrating on nylon. In 1988
its operations peaked with trading profits of Pounds 53m. However, profits
halved the following year. Fibres contributed to the materials division's
losses of Pounds 14m during the final quarter of last year.
ICI has already undertaken rationalisation at the fibres businesses. About
1,000 jobs were shed in 1991 and a further 800 are scheduled for this year.
The operation's Harrogate headquarters has been closed and a 20-staff
headquarters set up in Brussels.
However, in February Sir Denys said rationalisation at the fibres operations
had not created margins strong enough to produce satisfactory results. To
compete internationally against manufacturers in the Far East, Asia, ICI
would probably have to invest large sums in modern plant, believe analysts.
Further rationalisation of the European fibres industry appears inevitable,
warns Mr Wamsley. 'There may be further mergers or take-overs in the
man-made fibres industry, but none will mean anything unless capacity is
taken out,' he said.
</TEXT>
