<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / Abbey National sees gloomy year ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FURIOUS trading in Abbey National shares followed a gloomy forecast by the
banking group's chairman, Sir Christopher Tugendhat.
The volume of transactions for the day, at 12m, was the highest since the
company was launched in July 1989. Having risen before the annual meeting,
shares ended down 11 1/2 p for the day at 299 1/2 p.
Sir Christopher said: '1992 is proving to be a difficult year for Abbey
National. During the first quarter there has been a significant increase in
the level of inquiries from prospective house purchasers, but the political
uncertainties have put a brake on turning those inquiries into confirmed
business. Arrears and repossessions are at a higher level than expected and
this in turn will mean a higher level of provisioning.'
Abbey's chief executive, Mr Peter Birch, had made a more positive assessment
last month. 'I think we are over the worst in the housing market,' he said.
Analysts disagreed on whether the market made a realistic reaction. Mr John
Wriglesworth, building societies analyst at UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, described
the move as a 'thinly veiled profits warning', but added that the statement
had not affected his own profits forecast for the year, which remains at
Pounds 635m, compared with Pounds 618m last year. However, some analysts are
considering downgrading their forecasts from the Pounds 650m level to around
Pounds 620m.
Mr Chris Ellerton, analyst at SG Warburg, suspected the reaction was
overdone. He said the housing market had been widely forecast as a chief
victim of a hung parliament, and that the stock might have been 'a little
carried away' during post-election euphoria.
Stormy scenes punctuated the meeting, which was attended by around 1,400
shareholders. One shareholder attempted to move a motion not to increase the
final dividend, and to divert the money saved to mortgage rescue schemes.
Several shareholders complained about poor service or underperforming
accounts from the Abbey, and there was also an attack on its life assurance
questionnaires, which ask if applicants have been tested for the Aids
disease, but do not ask about smoking.
