<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / US-EC strategy agreed to break trade talks deadlock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US and the European Community yesterday agreed on a new strategy to try
to break the deadlock over agriculture that is bedevilling completion of the
Uruguay trade round.
Having exchanged what were described as 'new ideas' at a meeting in the
White House yesterday, the two sides committed themselves to try to reach an
agreement on agricultural subsidies by the end of June. Neither would
disclose what the proposals were and both agreed that no dramatic
'breakthrough' had been achieved yesterday.
Mr Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, said it was obvious
that the US-EC impasse over agriculture was holding up a new global trade
liberalisation pact. There was, he said, 'too much at stake' in the talks -
within the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (Gatt) - to allow this
impasse to remain. The US and the EC, he declared, 'are not in a mood to
pull back'.
In particular, he said he had made clear to President George Bush that,
regardless of the Uruguay Round, the EC was committed to reform of the
common agricultural policy (CAP).
This would entail, he said, smaller financial subventions, lower farm
production, more farm imports and fewer farm exports. On this basis, the EC
could make further proposals, as long as they were matched by concessions
from the US.
Mr Bush responded that he was now convinced that the EC was ready to go for
an early settlement. Right up to the White House meeting, which also
included Mr Anabal Cavalco da Silva, prime minister of Portugal and
currently head of the EC council of ministers, US officials had publicly
doubted that Mr Delors had brought to Washington a European consensus.
Even afterwards, some US reservations were apparent. Mrs Carla Hills, the US
trade representative, said that, though she was 'more optimistic today than
yesterday', Mr Delors still 'wants us to move further and his side to move
less'.
The EC's apparent willingness to depart from the agreed Uruguay Round text,
drafted by Mr Arthur Dunkel, the Gatt secretary general, was a concern, she
added.
Mrs Hills was even reluctant to characterise anything the EC delegation had
proposed as 'new'. Asked specifically if the EC had again raised the
so-called 'blue box, safe box' scenario, which would allow certain EC farm
subsidies to continue for another six years prior to a phase-out, she
replied 'those are the parameters we have always discussed,' implying that
they had been re-stated.
Mr Delors, however, though insisting that it was 'still more my wish than my
prognosis', argued that an EC-US agreement on agriculture by the end of June
'means we can relaunch a discussion in Geneva on all the other subjects' in
the Uruguay Round draft.
It emerged that at the White House the trade discussions focused only on
agriculture. Other general topics covered included the situation in
Yugoslavia, aid to the former Soviet Union and the Middle East.
Keating warns of Pacific trade bloc; Bush senses new ideas, Page 8
</TEXT>
