<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / Improvement in service sector heralds recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EARLY SIGNS of recovery heralded by the British Chambers of Commerce
yesterday were confined mainly to service industries.
For the manufacturing sector the outlook remained gloomy. Companies saw
orders in the first quarter of this year fall for the eighth consecutive
quarter, albeit at a slower rate. Yet the chambers were confident that
manufacturing industries would soon follow the service sector out of
recession.
'As manufacturing accounts for around a quarter of GDP it is clear that
recession, as measured by orders in the UK, is almost over,' says the
report. 'If these trends continue a return to growing sales deliveries in
both manufacturing and services is expected during the second quarter of
1992.'
The service sector, which went into recession later than the manufacturing
sector and suffered a more shallow decline in output, resumed growth for the
first time since mid 1990 in the first quarter of the year.
According to the survey of 8,810 companies, slightly more than half of which
were service providers, domestic demand for services was beginning to
improve after more than a year of contraction.
The report says the growth was almost entirely due to a remarkably strong
performance by small companies, while bigger service providers - those with
more than 20 employees - were still suffering a decline in orders.
Mr Richard Brown, director of policy for the chambers, said: 'This suggests
that the more nimble small companies are better able to take the initiative
and make the most of the increase in demand.'
While exports in both the manufacturing and service sector continued to
grow, a worrying trend was a slowing in the rate of growth in service-sector
exports. Mr Brown said the slowdown could be ascribed to difficult global
trading conditions. 'You can't keep up the rate of growth if all your
markets are slowing down. There are still very strong markets in the Far
East and Middle East, but Europe seems to be slowing down,' he said.
Low investment remained a problem for both sectors. The report notes that
investment plans in both sectors continued to be revised downwards.
While many investment decisions were probably delayed because of electoral
uncertainties, the chambers said falling investment in the manufacturing
sector raised the question of whether British industry would be able to
sustain growth at this point in the recovery without the foundations of
solid investment.
Lower interest rates remained the factor most likely to improve company
prospects in both sectors, with a balance of 80 per cent of manufacturers
and more than a third of service providers saying interest rates were their
main concern.
The number of manufacturing companies working at full capacity fell to its
lowest level with just 19 per cent of those surveyed operating at full
capacity. In the service sector there was a small fall in the number of
companies working at full capacity.
Employment continued to fall. Nationally, a balance of more than a quarter
of large manufacturers and more than a fifth of service-sector employers
expected to reduce their workforces.
Job prospects were most buoyant in Northern Ireland and north-east England.
In manufacturing, only Merseyside employers recorded growth in jobs - almost
entirely due to a few large companies - but this was outweighed by a big
reduction in service-sector employment in the region.
Recruitment across the country remained low, but skilled manual,
professional and managerial staff remained the hardest to recruit. The
easiest region for skilled manual workers to find jobs in manufacturing was
south-west England followed by the north-east where recruitment difficulties
were the highest.
After a sharp fall in business confidence at the end of last year,
expectations remained broadly unchanged in the first three months of the
year, the report concludes. 'Continuing high levels of insolvency and
unemployment, coupled with a sustained decline in the housing market, will
have done little to boost consumer confidence or demand.'
Quarterly Economic Survey. Association of British Chambers of Commerce, 9
Tufton Street, London SW1P 3QB. Pounds 30.
</TEXT>
