<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / British Chambers of Commerce Survey: Upturn in regions may
be fragile
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AREAS OF weakness across the regions could cast doubt on the sustainability
of the UK's apparent recovery, the British Chambers of Commerce said
yesterday.
Growth in domestic manufacturing in north-east England - the region leading
the country out of recession with the strongest growth rate - faltered in
the first quarter of this year.
A similar slowdown in East Anglia, a further region where growth last year
was more encouraging than elsewhere, prompted the chambers to question the
sustainability of growth in some areas.
'In the cases of the north-east and East Anglia, we are looking at the
inability of two regions to sustain growth, given that there is no growth in
the regions around them,' said Mr Richard Brown, director of policy.
In spite of the easing in the north-east, growth in the domestic market of
its manufacturing sector remained the highest in the country.
The fragility of the recovery was further highlighted by a slowdown of
growth in the service sectors of the same regions.
In the north-east service-sector growth fell back slightly while service
providers in East Anglia suffered a strong fall with more companies
suffering lower sales than in the fourth quarter of last year.
Merseyside's economy was the weakest of all the regions. The chambers said
the area's economy seemed to be 'swinging back and forward'.
Impressive growth in service-sector exports in the last quarter of last year
was followed by a sharp decline in exports.
However, in the same quarter manufacturers began to see a recovery in export
orders. Investment plans in the region fell to a 'drastically low level'.
London saw a turnaround in manufacturing for the domestic and export markets
at the start of the year. In the last quarter of last year more companies in
London reported that sales were decreasing rather than increasing. This
trend was sharply reversed in the first quarter of this year.
</TEXT>
