<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / Class divide still rules some company canteens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE OUT of 10 companies with canteens still divide workers from bosses at
mealtimes, according to a survey published today.
It is called the 'multi-status dining operation' in the catering trade
although others might describe it as another example of the British
obsession with class. Companies offer traditional canteen fare in basic
surroundings for the manual workers; staff restaurants for white-collar
workers; and dining rooms for the high-ups.
Trade journal Caterer and Hotelkeeper - which commissioned the study along
with Touche Ross, the management consultants - believes the practice is
quintessentially British. In most Japanese or American companies, all
employees eat in one room, the study points out.
The survey, which criticises the multi-status operation, examined the
catering policies of 200 of the UK's largest companies and talked to 2,000
employees. It says: 'As well as being more expensive, multi-status is
frowned upon by management philosophies as being at the root of the 'them
and us' syndrome.'
However, the survey finds common ground between the classes in the food
consumed. There is a continuing attachment to chips across all divisions,
with 80 per cent of employees saying they should remain on the menu. Healthy
eating seems to be making some impact on desserts: fresh fruit salad and
yoghurt are popular, although syrup sponge has a strong following.
Most employers expect to subsidise catering or at the least break even -
although 16 per cent make a profit out of the operation. There is little
sign that companies are cutting catering expenditure because of the
recession.
The study concludes: 'Perhaps the reasons for the survival of staff
restaurants virtually intact is that parent companies want to maintain
workforce morale during periods of redundancies or other severe money-saving
schemes. Many firms take the view it is better to keep those unaffected by
redundancies sweet and maintain their subsidised employee-feeding package.'
</TEXT>
