<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / Teachers call for set levels of staffing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NATIONAL regime for funding and staffing state schools in England and
Wales was demanded yesterday by the NASUWT, the second-largest teachers'
union.
If implemented, the reform would in effect entail abolition of the financial
role of local education authorities in England and Wales. It also would curb
the powers being conferred on head teachers and governing bodies through the
local management of schools.
NASUWT leaders told the union's annual conference yesterday that the change
was an inevitable consequence of government policies on the opting out of
schools and on capping of local authority spending.
Declaring the general election 'a watershed in the administration and
organisation of the state education service', delegates carried a motion
calling for 'all schools to be staffed on an agreed national model'.
Funding of teachers' salaries would then be 'a direct charge on the
Exchequer', with terms and conditions settled by the profession's
independent review body in conjunction with a new national forum
representing employers, unions and the government.
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, NASUWT general secretary, said: 'This is a challenge to
the government to take their own national curriculum and pupil-testing
seriously.
'At the moment we have the nonsensical situation that teachers are being
made redundant because their pay award is not properly funded by some local
authorities whose spending is capped by the government.'
The conference, meeting in Scarborough, also urged the establishment of 'a
collegiate and collaborative' structure in schools, with an end to the
existing differentiated salary structure and performance pay for
individuals.
At a press conference later, Mr de Gruchy condemned moves by opted-out
schools not to recognise teachers' unions.
He said the refusal of Wilson's School in Sutton, south-west London, to
negotiate with NASUWT representatives over proposed redundancies would be
'vigorously resisted' and could lead to a strike.
Grant-maintained schools are not obliged by law to recognise unions, and
they are not bound to follow the recommendations of the teachers' pay review
body.
However, Mr de Gruchy urged staff in grant-maintained schools to press for
them to do so, even if pay increases larger than the national award were on
offer.
Mr de Gruchy said: 'This is the not-too-hidden agenda of the Tory right  -
breaking the teacher unions.'
Editorial comment, Page 22
</TEXT>
