<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / Annual reports marked 'could do better'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANNUAL reports of British companies vary widely in their ability to
communicate information, according to an analysis by Meridian Design
Associates, a consultancy firm.
It says the typical report is 56 pages long, printed on A4 paper; contains a
vacuous 'vision statement'; has five sub-standard photographs; and a reader
needs 75 seconds to pick out the five most important facts about the
company.
Allied Lyons, Tesco and Tate &amp; Lyle rated highest among the top 100 quoted
companies on a scale assessing the financial information, illustrations and
lay-out of their annual reports for 1990 or last year.
The survey contains valuable lessons for businesses hoping to improve the
presentation of information provided to shareholders. 'Most companies could
easily do a better job of conveying basic information,' it concludes.
Meridian argues that annual reports have become 'big business', particularly
as a result of expanded share ownership. It estimates that 25m copies of
annual reports were produced last year. It says reports should have two main
tasks: to provide comprehensive and accurate information and to convey a
company image.
The firm concedes that annual report designers are often accused of
preferring pictures to words and graphics to information content.
'Fundamentally unsound companies often employ fancy devices to distract
attention from the unpalatable realities,' it says.
As a result, it attempted to produce an objective index by which to judge
annual reports, based on three criteria:
Financial information: the number of seconds (ideally no more than 100) in
which a busy analyst could find earnings per share, net asset value, and
three other facts which give a feel of the company and could be used to
support a buy, sell or hold recommendation.
Clarity: marks were awarded for signposts to help the reader, including a
contents page (Reed International did not have one), an index (only six
reports had them), a corporate profile and a vision statement (55 per cent
had one of the two), and a direc-tory of main subsidiaries with contact
phone numbers. Visuals: an assessment of the use of photographs and
graphics, with points deducted from a base score of 20 for poor quality and
irrelevant or confusing pictures.
Too often report pages present 'a jumble of different images' with too many
illustrations, Meridian says. Photographs are frequently blurred, badly lit
or have the appearance of being taken in photo booths. Sun Alliance, the
insurance company, and P&amp;O, the shipping and property group, were the only
reports which had no photographs at all.
Privatisation appears to have had little impact on the quality of reports.
The electricity companies generally had few comments on prospects as well as
poor photographs. Water company reports suffered from 'dull pictures,
tedious text and no real signposting'.
The Annual Report. Meridian Design Associates, 424 Kingston Rd, London SW20
8LL. Pounds 365.
</TEXT>
