<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / Accountants' salaries show sharp increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANTS' salaries have risen sharply in the past year in spite of the
recession, a survey by Hays Management Consultants showed yesterday.
Average base salaries rose by 10.3 per cent in the 12 months to February 1
this year, down slightly from an increase of 11.1 per cent in the previous
year.
The consultants listed pay by experience category and said that the average
salary for a first-year accountancy trainee early this year was Pounds
14,567. For a newly-qualified accountant it was Pounds 21,226, for someone
with four to five years' experience after qualifying Pounds 27,627 and for
someone having worked nine to 12 years after qualification Pounds 43,836.
The only salary increase which was larger this year than last was for
accountants who had qualified four to five years earlier, for which the
figure grew by 11 per cent compared with 10 per cent last year.
Pay for tax professionals was up 8.1 per cent, compared with 9.6 per cent in
the previous 12 months. Average base salaries under the experience
categories were Pounds 15,950, Pounds 24,711, Pounds 32,915 and Pounds
45,207.
For industrial and service-sector companies, the average base salary was
Pounds 14,303 for first-year trainees, Pounds 20,924 for newly-qualified
staff, Pounds 27,121 for those four to five years after qualifying, and
Pounds 42,244 for those qualified for nine to 12 years.
In the public sector, salaries in the same categories were Pounds 14,146,
Pounds 19,965, Pounds 25,461 and Pounds 40,965. In finance, they were Pounds
16,346, Pounds 23,971, Pounds 31,792 and Pounds 53,335 respectively. The
salaries paid to those in private practice were within these ranges.
The seventh annual Hays survey covered accountants from 522 organisations
and tax professionals from 127. The survey also covered a range of benefits
offered to the employees. Only 7 per cent of organisations did not provide
company cars. The average list price of cars provided for a newly qualified
accountant was Pounds 12,000, rising to about Pounds 19,000 for someone with
nine to 12 years' service after qualifying.
Pensions and company cars were the most common benefits offered, although a
growing number of organisations was reviewing changes in the provision of
these benefits. The usual number of holidays was 25 days per year.
The largest growth in accountants' salaries came in the oil industry, with
that for newly-qualified staff rising 27.4 per cent on last year and 24.2
per cent for those four to five years after qualifying.
Accountants and Taxation Professionals Remuneration Survey. Hay Management
Consultants, 52 Grosvenor Gdns, London SW1W 0AU. Pounds 625 to participants.
</TEXT>
