FT  23 APR 92 / City workers accused of complacency on security
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and BETHAM HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPLACENCY among companies and workers about security in the City of London
was criticised yesterday. The comments followed an IRA bomb 10 days ago
which killed three people and caused extensive damage.
Mr John Wyatt, a security and bomb-disposal expert, said: 'Some companies
feel they are faced with a situation they cannot understand and are
incapable of taking any measures that will help them.'
Police said the scale of damage caused by the St Mary Axe bomb had made
companies take the possibility of terrorist attack seriously but employees
were less concerned. Two meetings for company representatives had attracted
300 managers, while only three people had attended a well-advertised police
meeting on Tuesday for the public.
As the city continued clearing up, getting back to business appeared to take
priority over tightening security.
At Commercial Union, whose head offices on 10 floors of the 23-storey CU
tower took the full force of the blast contractors are concentrating on
making the building weatherproof. envisage extra security precautions. It is
expected to move its HQ into the Cutlers Exchange building on the eastern
edge of the City.
Companies which have moved into temporary offices such as Sanwa, the
Japanese bank, said the main priority had been to ensure that dealing rooms
could operate normally again. Mr Noboshi Kamei, Sanwa's deputy managing
director, said: 'It is impossible to prevent a bomb disaster from
happening.'
Chief Inspector Peter Moore of the City Police said: 'Businesses have begun
to realise the necessity to have back-up systems for the retention of
computer data, financial information or whatever.' The lack of interest in
Tuesday's meeting had been partly because the incident had gone from the
headlines.
The judge in the Birmingham Six case last night admitted he felt unhappy
about the verdict which sentenced the men to 16 years in prison before they
were freed on appeal. Lord Bridge said on Thames Television's This Week
programme that the judiciary should take a 'share of the responsibility' for
injustices. He was unhappy, but did not feel guilty about the Birmingham
Six.
Letters, Page 23
A ROW over the leaking of a secret Scotland Yard report on the IRA to the
Irish Times intensified yesterday with allegations that M15, the British
intelligence service may have been responsible.
Mr Tam Dalyell, Labour MP for Linlithgow said it was 'more than likely' that
M15 was responsible.
The row follows the sending to the prime minister of a Home Office report
which discusses the possibility of M15 taking control of intelligence
gathering from the police.
Scotland Yard last night would not confirm a report that senior officers
were convinced that the document leaked to the Irish Times formed part of an
M15 'dirty tricks' campaign. It has set up an internal inquiry. The document
sugggests the Metropolitan Police's anti-terrorist squad had 'little'
intelligence on the IRA members responsible for some 17 killings in more
than four attacks on the mainland since 1988.
</TEXT>
