<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / World Trade News: Bush senses new ideas in trade's
atmospherics - Jurek Martin and Nancy Dunne on contrasting views of
yesterday's Gatt talks in Washington
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL may have been sweetness and light on the White House lawn after the EC
lunch yesterday. But before the president could host an evening barbecue for
the Washington Redskins football team, US and European officials were
putting conspicuously different spin on what had actually been agreed.
On the US side, the Bush presidential campaign, which drives the agenda
these days in Washington, had decreed this to be Trade Week, of which the
meeting with the EC delegation along with the ever flickering hopes of
rescuing the Uruguay Round were to be the centrepiece.
In the event of total failure, US officials had carefully depressed
expectations, blaming the impasse in Gatt, the president's highest trade
priority, on the EC's inability to fit its internal farm reforms into the
world-wide agriculture trade rules proposed by Mr Arthur Dunkel, the Gatt
director general.
President Bush was thus able to squeeze some drama and good news out of the
2 1/2 hour meeting with the announcement that 'new ideas', presented by both
sides, had convinced him that the EC was determined on an early settlement.
In sum, this could be dressed up as a solid day's presidential work, looking
after the affairs of the nation.
The substance, however, was still seen by some in the administration to be a
little wanting. Mrs Carla Hills, the US trade representative, pronounced
herself 'more optimistic' than before - but only because 'the atmospherics
were good'.
But she admitted that after three years of wrangling over farm products
there was not much new to be said. 'If you have variables, you can mix
around, so it's an alternate way to proceed, I suppose that can be seen as a
new idea,' she said. 'Several alternatives were suggested. I have thought of
these ideas in the past and I will continue to think about them, and other
combinations.'
She stuck to the Dunkel text, which the EC is hoping to see modified, and
said that if the EC cannot accept it, it must find some formula for
achieving something equivalent.
Mr Jacques Delors, the EC Commission president, on the other hand, really
did seem to ooze confidence that something significant had been achieved, or
at least attempted. Even his own Washington-based delegation, which had
known little of his plans before his arrival, confessed to being surprised.
At breakfast, Mr Delors had characterised what he would say to Mr Bush as
'modest'. If Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany, a far more important
personage, had been able to achieve no breakthrough at Camp David in March,
he could hardly be anything other than modest, he said.
By mid-afternoon, mere modesty had been translated into 'new ideas' and then
into a 'commitment' (not the words of the EC president, but of Mr Bush
himself). Thus emboldened, Mr Delors was able to foresee the time when, the
agricultural impasse with the US out of the way, everything in the Uruguay
Round could then fall into place and be signed, sealed and delivered.
To one close observer of Mr Delors, he has undergone something of a
Damascene conversion in recent months. He now not only really does believe
that a failure in the Uruguay Round would grievously harm the global economy
but also that the Common Agricultural Policy, which blocks the agreement,
needs total transformation.
Thus, on this interpretation, he really did have something new to say to Mr
Bush and apparently succeeded in impressing the president. However, actual
negotiations, now that the political will has been established, will return
to the murky worlds of 'blue boxes', 'green lights', 'peace clauses' and
other obfuscations of the reality of the need to cut farm subsidies.
Presidents, of Europe or the US, rarely get that deep into the negotiating
woodwork.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-11829</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDWA1ADSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920423
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / World Trade News: Keating warns of Pacific bloc if Gatt
fails - Australian leader blames 'indifferent' Europeans as the EC and US
put a positive gloss on their Uruguay Round talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JAKARTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Paul Keating, Australia's prime minister, warned yesterday that a Pacific
trading group might emerge to counter European and North American blocs if
Gatt's Uruguay Round trade talks fail.
Speaking on the second day of his official visit to Indonesia, Mr Keating
blamed the 'indifferent progress' of trade negotiations on 'a lack of
determination on the part of the Europeans to make the Gatt round succeed'.
He characterised the EC as 'very much a United States of Europe'. In
response to the EC and the development of the North American Free Trade Area
(Nafta) grouping the US, Canada and Mexico, a third trade area in the
Pacific might emerge, he warned.
A Pacific trade bloc would not be in the interests of Australia, Mr Keating
said. To prevent its occurrence, he called on the US in particular to review
its policy towards Asia.
'It is important that the US plays a role beyond its continental boundaries
in trade in Asia,' he said.
'The policy of the United States should be broader, deeper, wider than
simply the strategic policy of the US defence department or the US navy.'
Mr Keating suggested that the Asia Pacific Economic Co-operation group
(Apec) should be used as a forum where 'the two largest economies (the US
and Japan) can resolve some of their differences'.
Japan and the US are important trading partners for Australia, Mr Keating
said, and 'we don't want our (Australia's) loyalties tested between these
two friendly countries'.
Australia is likely to find resistance amongst some Asian countries to
giving Apec an enhanced role, especially if it were to undermine existing
trade groups such as the Association of South East Asian Nations (Asean).
Mr Ali Alatas, Indonesia's foreign minister, said his government saw
'validity' in Mr Keating's proposal but wished 'to mull it over some more
 .and see when the best time would be to initiate this idea'.
The two countries yesterday signed economic and political agreements on
fisheries, double taxation and extradition. They represented evidence of
Australia's determination to look towards Asia for its economic future, Mr
Keating said,
Both countries sought to defuse any 'misunderstanding' over East Timor
following statements by President Suharto the previous night that Indonesia
would not accept foreign interference in its domestic affairs.
Earlier, at a meeting with Mr Alatas, Mr Keating had suggested that East
Timor, the former Portuguese territory annexed by Indonesia in 1976, should
be given special territory status. He also expressed concern at the
prosecution of East Timorese nationalists.
Mr Alatas said yesterday that President Suharto's remarks had been
misinterpreted.
'What he (President Suharto) was trying to say was: 'Don't misunderstand
us.' We do accept criticism, we do accept friendly advice.'
Mr Keating told the Indonesian Foreign Policy Forum yesterday that East
Timor had received 'disproportionate attention'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-11830</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CDWA1ADRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920423
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / World Trade News: Nissan will bear brunt of cuts in car
sales to US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NISSAN, Japan's second largest car maker, appears set to bear the brunt of
the self-imposed 'voluntary' cut in direct car exports to the US agreed last
month by Japan's Ministry of International Trade and Industry (Miti).
The company's import quota for this year will fall by at least 44 per cent
to below 300,000, from a quota of 532,276 and actual exports of 324,132 last
year, according to Japanese industry sources quoted by Reuter.
The cut compares with an overall reduction of 28.2 per cent, to 1.65m from
2.3m vehicles, set as an informal imports ceiling by Miti in March because
of growing friction with Washington.
Exports to the US from Japan last year are estimated at only 1.73m vehicles,
against 1.85m in 1990. But Miti's lower ceiling has been derided by the US
motor industry, with Ford's chairman and chief executive, Mr Harold Poling,
saying Japan has 'learned nothing' about the need to balance its trade with
the US.
According to Japanese motor industry insiders, Toyota's quota will be just
above 480,000, down 21.2 per cent from 1991 and just 6 per cent in terms of
actual 1991 exports of 510,489.
Honda's quota is under 320,000, down 24.5 per cent from its 1991 quota and 6
per cent from its actual exports Mitsubishi's quota will be above 150,000,
down from 193,658 and actual exports of 165,284, and Mazda below 200,000,
down from 226,116 and exports of 210,208
Fuji Heavy Industries (Subaru) will be above 70,000, down from 106,805 and
exports of 51,158. Isuzu will be above 100,000, down from 124,210 and up
from actual exports of 93,100 last year. Suzuki will be above 30,000, down
from 64,552, and actual exports of 30,236. Daihatsu, with a 20,000 quota
last year, is pulling out.
</TEXT>
