<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / French prepare for Maastricht debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, LUXEMBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE'S Socialist government yesterday adopted a draft law to revise the
constitution, a critical step towards ratifying the Maastricht treaty on
European union.
The draft was immediately sent to the National Assembly for debate; the
government said it hoped revision and ratification could be completed before
the summer holidays.
However, the constitutional changes will be the object of a political
barrage from the Socialist government's conservative opponents, even those
who in principle support Maastricht objectives.
Mr Francois Bayrou, secretary general of the centre-right UDF umbrella
grouping, while declaring that 'there is no other possible destination for
France than Maastricht', said his party would demand and obtain amendments.
The main aspects of the treaty dealt with in the new constitution law but
disputed by the opposition are plans for a single currency and the provision
for residents from other EC countries to vote and be elected in local
elections.
The government's problem is that the Socialist party does not command an
absolute majority in the National Assembly. The Communists are hostile to
the treaty and, on the right, the Gaullists are hostile to the government.
The government should make good the shortfall with the help of the centrists
and UDF members, most of whom support the EC. But the UDF, together with the
RPR Gaullist party, plans to set conditions for its agreement in parliament,
which could create uncertainties for the parliamentary arithmetic.
President Franc,ois Mitterrand has made clear he wants the constitutional
revision enacted in a purely parliamentary process. In the first phase, the
two houses would pass the legislation by a simple majority. In the second,
the two houses sitting together in Versailles in a so-called Congress would
pass the same revision by a three-fifths majority.
As an alternative second phase, the government can put the constitutional
revision to a referendum.
In either case, the second phase could be risky for the government. If the
Gaullists mobilise additional support for restrictive conditions, they could
prevent a three-fifths majority in Congress. But if the government opts for
a referendum, it would put on the line not just the treaty but also the
position of President Mitterrand, whose popularity is at a record low.
In the last resort, the Gaullist party will be reluctant to take
responsibility for bringing down the Maastricht treaty. Mr Jacques Chirac,
Gaullist leader, has this week started to back away from his demand for a
referendum.
If the constitutional revision does go through, parliamentary ratification
is likely to become a foregone conclusion.
Reuter adds from Luxembourg: The government yesterday urged the Grand
Duchy's parliament to approve the treaty without a referendum. Mr Jacques
Santer, prime minister, said the referendum as demanded by the main
opposition group could turn into a vote against the 113,000 foreigners
living in Luxembourg.
As in France, debate in Luxembourg centres on the clause allowing residents
from other EC states to stand and vote in local elections. Recent polls show
support for European union in Luxembourg dwindled from 83 per cent to 35 per
cent in the year to March.
Final push, Page 22
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
