<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / Sterling surges on recovery hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STRONG SUPPORT for sterling from Japanese and German investors and growing
hopes of a UK economic recovery yesterday pushed the pound to its highest
close against the D-Mark in London for more than seven months.
The pound gained 1 1/2 pfennigs against a weaker German currency to close in
London at DM2.9325, opening up the possibility that the government could
safely cut borrowing rates from their current 10.5 per cent.
Sterling's continued strength - it has overtaken both the Danish krone and
the French franc in the European exchange rate mechanism (ERM) since the
election - coincided with publication of two surveys pointing to an economic
recovery, albeit a slow one.
A quarterly survey of 8,000 companies by the British Chambers of Commerce
showed that in the first quarter the service sector resumed growth for the
first time since mid-1990, while the rate of decline in manufacturing
slowed.
This message was reinforced in Washington by the International Monetary Fund
which said the UK economy was about to move into recovery. It warned that
Britain would have the slowest growth rate this year among the Group of
Seven leading industrial countries.
Indications of brighter prospects for the UK after the recession which
started around mid-1990 persuaded more international investors to switch
funds into sterling.
But there are still no signs that either the Treasury or the Bank of
England, through its money market operations, are in a hurry to cut base
rates, unchanged since September.
Widespread support for the pound, particularly from overseas investors,
started after the Conservative election victory on April 9. Another factor
behind the more positive sentiment towards the UK by many overseas investors
appears to be the clear-cut nature of the win and the prospect of a
relatively long period of political stability.
Yesterday, sterling climbed to within 2 pfennigs of its central DM2.95 rate
in the ERM, while it gained 1.5 cents against the dollar to Dollars 1.7630.
Sterling's strength in London - it later eased a touch in New York to
DM2.93115 and Dollars 1.7625 - boosted prices in government gilt-edged
securities by up to a quarter of a point.
The mood of optimism was not shared by investors on the London stock market,
where the FT-SE 100 index closed 18 lower at 2,607.8.
The feeling that any recovery will be fragile was underlined by the British
Chambers of Commerce report which warned that employment prospects remained
gloomy. It said the jobless total could climb from 2.65m to 3m by the end of
the year.
In addition, rapidly falling factory investment during the recession could
lead to manufacturers lagging behind their overseas rivals, once the
recovery gathered pace. However, export orders continued to grow in both
manufacturing and services, although the service sector was unable to
sustain recent strong levels of growth.
Another reminder of the weak state of demand in the UK in the first three
months came from Bank of England figures on the money supply.
These showed that banks and building societies last month received a net
repayment of Pounds 500m on sterling loans by companies and individuals.
This was the first time since records began in 1982 that monthly lending had
failed to show a net rise.
