<HEADLINE>
FT  23 APR 92 / UK Company News: Downturn at GT Management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GT MANAGEMENT, the investment management group which is owned by the Bank in
Liechtenstein, saw pre-tax profits fall by 7 per cent in 1991 despite strong
growth in its US mutual fund business.
Funds under management rose from Pounds 5.3bn to Pounds 6.6bn, but
commission and fee income rose only 4 per cent to Pounds 67.3m (Pounds
64.7m). That reflected a reduction in initial commission income (the charge
made when funds are purchased by retail investors) from the high levels
achieved in 1990.
In addition, the 1990 profit figure of Pounds 20.9m included an exceptional
item of Pounds 2.9m. If that item was excluded, the 1991 pre-tax figure of
Pounds 19.4m actually represented a 7 per cent rise.
The US mutual funds business, based in San Francisco, saw funds under
management rise 31 per cent to nearly Dollars 4bn (Pounds 2.2bn). US retail
funds now represent a third of assets under GT's management. Mr Peter
Stevens, chief executive, also said that the UK pension fund business grew
by 25 per cent last year.
GT has set up an operation in Dublin, where it intends to concentrate the
administration of its offshore funds, which are currently domiciled in a
wide range of locations - including the Cayman Islands and the Netherlands
Antilles.
</TEXT>
