FT  23 APR 92 / World Trade News: Philip Morris buys into Czech cigarette
maker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PRAGUE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PHILIP Morris of the US has won a bid to buy into Czech cigarette
manufacturer Tabak Kutna Hora, acquiring 30 per cent of the stock for
Dollars 104.4m, (Pounds 58.9m), the Hospodarske Noviny (Economic News) daily
reported yesterday, Reuter reports from Prague.
Czech deputy prime minister Mr Jan Strasky said the company would invest
Dollars 140m in updating Kutna Hora's obsolete technology. The Czech
government would retain 35 per cent of the stock, and 27 per cent would be
distributed to the population under Czechoslovakia's scheme of coupon
privatisation, the daily said.
This year, about Dollars 9bn of assets will be handed over to Czechs and
Slovaks against government-issued coupons, making some 8.5m citizens
shareholders in former communist state property. Consumption of cigarettes
in Czechoslovakia, where 38 per cent of the population are regular smokers,
has been steadily rising and is now at just over 2,000 cigarettes per capita
a year.
