FT  22 APR 92 / International Capital Markets: Standard &amp; Poor's places US
airlines on credit watch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT and AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STANDARD &amp; Poor's, the US ratings agency, yesterday placed seven US airlines
on credit watch with negative implications, AP-DJ reports from New York.
The action affects about Dollars 19.5bn of securities issued by Alaska Air,
AMR, Delta Air Lines, NWA, Southwest Airlines, UAL and USAir and their
subsidiaries.
On Wall Street, shares in most of the quoted airlines were sharply lower
yesterday, in reaction to American's downward adjustment in fares announced
on Monday, adds Nikki Tait.
AMR, American's parent company, lost Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 68 1/2 ; UAL,
holding company for United Airlines, one of its big rival, eased Dollars 3
to Dollars 125; Delta Air Lines, the last of the 'Big Three,' lost Dollars 1
1/4 to Dollars 58 3/4 .
USAir, a financially weaker carrier and one of those leading the current
price competition, slipped  3/8 to Dollars 13 1/8 . Southwest Airlines, a
highly competitive smaller carrier based in Dallas, lost Dollars 1 at
Dollars 36 1/8.
