<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 92 / International Capital Markets: CBOT wins approval for
pollution futures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARBARA DURR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT) has received approval from the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission for its novel pollution futures, or 'Clean Air
Futures' as the CBOT calls them.
These are contracts based on the sulphur dioxide emission allowances that
will be issued by the US Environmental Protection Agency under the 1990
Clean Air Act.
These permits to pollute will be tradeable among the companies, primarily
electric utilities, that will receive them. Those companies that have
installed cleaner technologies will be in a position to sell their permits
to those who still cannot meet the more restrictive air standards.
Mr William O'Connor, the exchange's chairman, called the new contracts 'the
most exciting development in our industry since the introduction of interest
rate futures 15 years ago.'
The CBOT is still waiting for a decision by the EPA on its application to
administer the annual auction of the emission allowances. The first auction
is scheduled for March 1993 and the futures are expected to start trading
before then.
</TEXT>
