<TEXT>
STORAGE technology's shares plummeted by more than 20 per cent yesterday
when the manufacturer of computer data storage systems announced
lower-than-expected earnings and said testing of its much-heralded new
product, the Iceberg disk array, had slipped behind schedule.
The stock price fell from a Monday close of Dollars 56 1/4 to close at
Dollars 45 yesterday.
Net income for the first quarter was Dollars 12.5m, or 30 cents per share,
compared with Dollars 13.4m, or 36 cents per share, in the same period last
year.
Analysts had been projecting first-quarter earnings of about 52 cents per
share.
Revenue for the quarter totalled Dollars 333.7m, an 8 per cent decline from
Dollars 361.2m in the first quarter of 1991.
'While results for the first quarter fell somewhat below our expectations,
we remain optimistic about our prospects for the year,' said Mr Ryal Poppa,
chairman.
Storage Technology's stock rose sharply in January, when the company
announced Iceberg, an advanced disk array product for mainframe computers.
Analysts said that it appeared unlikely the company would install Iceberg at
customer sites until the third quarter rather than in the current quarter as
had been expected.
