<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 92 / International Company News: US banking results offer
evidence of recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Wells Fargo, the California-based banking group, jumped 14.9 per
cent yesterday after it reported first-quarter financial results which
dipped from a year ago but were better than Wall Street had been expecting.
Several other leading US banks - Chemical Banking, Banc One, Mellon Bank and
Bankers Trust - yesterday reported results that also underlined the gradual
recovery in the industry from the severe difficulties of the past two years.
Wells Fargo, which was hit hard by losses on its real estate portfolio in
1991, reported earnings of Dollars 119m, or Dollars 2.09 a share, in the
first quarter, down from Dollars 152m, or Dollars 2.86, in the same period
of last year.
However, some analysts had been expecting earnings per share as low as 80
cents, and in trading on the New York Stock Exchange the company's stock
closed in New York at Dollars 76 1/8 , up Dollars 9 7/8 .
The company's loan-loss provision was Dollars 215m, compared with Dollars
700m in the fourth quarter of last year, and Dollars 85m a year ago.
Net interest income increased 8 per cent to Dollars 680m, compared with
Dollars 631m a year earlier. Substantially all the increase was due to its
higher net interest margin - 5.70 per cent, compared with 5.06 per cent -
partially offset by lower earning assets.
Mr Carl Reichardt, Wells Fargo's chairman, said that 'economic recovery
around the nation is still fragile and in much of California we are still
waiting for some clear signs of a turnaround'.
Chemical Banking, which at the end of last year merged with Manufacturers
Hanover, a rival New York money centre bank, reported a 44 per cent increase
in net income to Dollars 260m, or Dollars 1 a share, from Dollars 181m, or
84 cents.
Mr John McGillicuddy, chairman, said there had been strong results in many
key earnings components: higher net interest income; an increase in trading
revenues; and improvements in several fee-based banking businesses.
The provision for losses was Dollars 375m, compared with Dollars 450m in the
fourth quarter of last year and Dollars 279m a year ago. Net interest income
rose 18 per cent to Dollars 1.115bn, while non-interest revenue rose 16 per
cent to Dollars 810m.
Banc One, the rapidly expanding Ohio-based super-regional bank, reported
record first-quarter earnings of Dollars 179m, or 86 cents a share, compared
with Dollars 130m, or 67 cents, in the same period of last year.
Mr John McCoy, chairman, said that continued strong retail loan demand and
core deposit growth had boosted the net interest margin, which rose from
6.17 per cent last year to 6.82 per cent.
Pittsburgh-based Mellon Bank reported net income of Dollars 86m, or Dollars
1.36 a share, in the first quarter, compared with Dollars 68m, or Dollars
1.25, a year ago.
The figures reflected increases in net interest revenue, trading and other
revenue, and service fee revenue. These gains were offset in part by
increases in operating expense and a Dollars 60m provision for loan losses,
up from Dollars 45m.
Bankers Trust, the New York investment banking group, reported a 9 per cent
increase in earnings to Dollars 175m, or Dollars 2.02 a share, up from
Dollars 160m, or Dollars 1.85m, in the first quarter of last year.
Mr Charles Sanford, chairman, said a broad range of businesses had
contributed to the increase, including asset management, fiduciary and
global finance.
Trading revenue was down 42 per cent from the Dollars 370m earned in last
year's first quarter.
Fiduciary and fund management revenue rose 15 per cent to Dollars 162m; fees
and commissions rose 18 per cent to Dollars 142m; and other non-interest
revenue rose from Dollars 9m to Dollars 63m, helped by gains from equity
investments. Non-interest expenses dropped 8 per cent to Dollars 535m.
</TEXT>
