<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 92 / NatWest adopts business-led charities policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Westminster Bank, Britain's biggest corporate supporter of charity,
has recast its community involvement policy to reflect the bank's business
priorities more closely.
The shift in emphasis follows a review of community support at NatWest,
which last year gave Pounds 13.7m in cash and other forms of support. A
number of large companies are reviewing the basis on which they support the
voluntary sector, and the business-led approach of NatWest is likely to be
adopted elsewhere.
NatWest has adopted the promotion of financial effectiveness and enterprise
as the central objective of its community investment policy. Requests for
money and other support will be assessed on whether they meet this
objective.
Many companies have until recently supported charity on a largely haphazard
basis, reflecting the enthusiasms of individual directors or the
eye-catching nature of charitable appeals.
The shift towards a more planned approach shows a growing recognition that
the private sector's now familiar involvement in the community must be
handled as seriously as any other business activity.
Ms Amanda Jordan, NatWest's head of community relations, said that in the
past the bank tended to support good ideas rather than focus on objectives.
'By focusing on those activities which we understand as a bank we hope that
we will be able to integrate the skills of our staff into the assistance we
offer, enabling us to give more than money,' she said.
In one of NatWest's special interest areas - education - the new focus will
be represented through support for schemes that promote financial literacy
in schools, mini-enterprise programmes and a 'Your Money Matters' teaching
package. Another of the bank's schemes helps the National Association of
Citizens' Advice Bureaux provide financial counselling, while plans are
being developed to help voluntary organisations improve their financial
management.
All applicants for NatWest's support will be sent leaflets explaining that
the bank's aim of helping to develop a more financially informed society and
encourage enterprise skills in the community will be the 'guiding principle'
for its involvement.
Ms Jordan accepted that the change of policy would lead to some requests for
support being turned down because they did not meet the new criteria -
although NatWest will meet existing commitments.
'But there are losers under any system,' she said. 'Like all large
companies, we receive far more appeals for help than we can meet. We hope
that a more structured approach will enhance the value of the support we are
able to give.'
Cuts in local-authority funding are leading an increasing number of
voluntary organisations to look to the private sector for support. NatWest
was one of about 40 companies which gave more than Pounds 1m in financial
and other support to charities last year, but growth in private-sector
charitable activity is being hit by the recession.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
