<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 92 / Parcelforce to get Pounds 250m boost
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has sanc-tioned a further Pounds 250m investment programme
into the Post Office's loss-making Parcelforce division.
The move was revealed as the Post Office yesterday announced that its
Datapost letter and document service, which is making a profit, is to be
merged into Parcelforce which last year made a loss before tax and
exceptional items of Pounds 131m.
The Post Office's two other divisions, Royal Mail and Post Office Counters,
both made profits. Overall the Post Office last year made a profit before
tax and exceptional items of Pounds 30m.
Earlier in the year Parcelforce received approval from the Department of
Trade and Industry to invest Pounds 250m over five years in eight new
automated sorting centres. About Pounds 50m has already been invested in
Parcelforce.
The DTI said that the fresh Pounds 250m investment would come from the Post
Office - possibly from cashflow as pre-tax profits had been just Pounds 30m.
Mr Peter Howarth, managing director of Parcelforce, said the merger with
Datapost - which guarantees a next-day service - would significantly reduce
Parcelforce's losses and would mean it was expected to be back in the black
by 1992-93.
Parcelforce is to publish its own accounts for the first time when the Post
Office produces its reports and accounts in July.
The new Parcelforce service will offer customers guaranteed deliveries for
10am and noon the next day, as well as access to Parcelforce's standard
services - which take between three and five days - throughout the Post
Office network.
Customers will now be offered a 25 per cent price differential between the
10am and noon services. The former will cost Pounds 17.20 and the latter
Pounds 13. The average price for a parcel will remain Pounds 2.70.
The merger will lead to a net loss of 100 jobs which the Post Office expects
to come from voluntary redundancies.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
