FT  22 APR 92 / Strike by Jobcentre staff
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRIKE by Jobcentre staff has failed to prevent the removal of protective
screens from unemployment benefit offices and Jobcentres, the government
claimed yesterday.
A total of 100 members of the CPSA Civil-Service union in three Jobcentres
in London and Bristol have been in dispute with the Department of Employment
for more than a year over a policy to make offices open-plan.
'The Employment Service remains committed to its open-plan programme,' the
department said.
The union claimed there had been an increase of 50 per cent in violent
attacks on Jobcentre staff since the removal of security screens and
counters began in 1989. The union's figures were disputed by the government.
An official announcement of the end of the dispute is expected today after
meetings between union officers and the strikers.
The union would not comment on claims that its members faced an embarrassing
climbdown, and said the strikers would look at proposals for a return to
work today. The action, which has included a one-day national strike, has
cost the union more than Pounds 1m.
