</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PHELPS DODGE, the largest US copper producer, saw operating income for its
mining operations drop in the first quarter to Dollars 76.9m from Dollars
113m a year ago, Reuter reports.
The group, which manufactures truck wheels and rims and is a leading
producer of carbon black, reported first-quarter net income down to Dollars
53.6m or Dollars 1.53 per share, compared with Dollars 77.3m or Dollars 2.23
a year ago.
It said first-quarter earnings were satisfactory in spite of continued slow
economies in many of its markets.
Group revenues for the quarter declined to Dollars 590.5m from Dollars
601.8m, while Phelps Dodge Mining saw its revenues slip to Dollars 301.5m,
compared with Dollars 314m a year ago.
Phelps cited lower copper prices and the closure of concentrator operations
at its Tyrone, New Mexico mine for the reduction in mining profits. It added
that reduced worldwide demand caused first-quarter copper prices to average
about 11 cents less than a year ago.
Phelps Dodge Industries reported an improvement in operating income, to
Dollars 20.3m from Dollars 16.8m a year ago.
The company said its share of copper production from worldwide operations
was 123,100 tons in the first quarter, compared with 130,400 tons a year
ago.
Copper sales from mine production were 127,700 tons, down from 138,500 tons
a year ago.
