<HEADLINE>
FT  22 APR 92 / International Company News: Citicorp doubles profits to
Dollars 183m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CITICORP, the largest banking group in the US, yesterday underscored the
battered sector's gradual return to financial health. It reported doubled
first-quarter profits and said it expected to regain its normal earnings
capacity by the year-end.
The bank, which has been seriously hurt by the crisis of the past two years
in the US and foreign real estate markets, is in the throes of a
reorganisation and capital building programme.
It reported net income of Dollars 183m, or 37 cents a share, compared to
Dollars 93m, or 17 cents, in the same period of 1991.
Continuing real estate problems were shown in its Dollars 1,23bn provision
for credit losses. This compared with Dollars 1.15bn in the fourth quarter
and Dollars 812m in the same period of last year. North American commercial
real estate comprised Dollars 588m of the total, compared with Dollars 562m
in the previous quarter and Dollars 175m a year ago.
Net write-offs totalled Dollars 997m, compared to Dollars 646m a year ago,
with North American real estate making up Dollars 362m, compared to Dollars
86m a year ago.
Mr John Reed, chairman, told the company's annual meeting yesterday that the
US real estate market and Citicorp's portfolio had stabilised. However, he
repeated that write-offs and other costs of commercial credit would continue
to be about as high in 1992 as in 1991.
He said the quarter's results reflected 'continuing progress towards the
successful completion of Citicorp's two-year programme to restore
profitability, build the company's capital position, and further develop
core business franchises.'
Net interest revenue rose 4 per cent to Dollars 1.83bn, while the net
interest margin rose to 3.76 per cent from 3.66 a year ago.
The operating margin - the difference between revenues and operating
expenses - rose 23 per cent to Dollars 1.7bn, helped by a 5 per cent growth
in revenue and a 6 per cent decline in expenses.
The bank's global consumer business produced a 61 per cent improvement in
net income to Dollars 260m, helped by solid credit card revenue growth in
the US, and a good performance in Germany. Operating expenses fell 5 per
cent.
The global finance business, which includes most of its commercial business,
reported net income down from Dollars 212m to Dollars 161m. Asia, Latin
American and the Middle East produced strong growth, but economic weakness
in the US Japan and Europe meant a Dollars 17m loss in these regions.
The bank's North American commercial real estate operations, which have been
reorganised as a separate reporting category, lost Dollars 463m, against
Dollars 124m a year ago.
The bank's tier one capital ratio, which it wants to boost to at least 5 per
cent by the end of 1993, improved 33 basis points in the quarter to 4.06 per
cent.
Mr Reed told the meeting: 'By the end of the year we expect to have restored
our normal earnings capacity and to have significantly improved our balance
sheet.'
</TEXT>
