<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 92 / International Company News: Hyundai to shift PC management
to US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KOREA'S Hyundai Group is to shift management of its worldwide personal
computer and computer peripherals operations to the US in an attempt to
improve its responsiveness to rapidly changing market conditions and gain
earlier access to advanced technologies.
In an unusual move for an Asian company, full management control, marketing,
product development and product assembly for the group's Dollars 750m
personal computer and peripherals business will be moved from Seoul to San
Jose, California.
The decision reflects Hyundai's recognition of the critical value of day to
day contact with suppliers and customers, said Mr Edward Thomas, the newly
appointed president of Hyundai's Information Systems Division.
Mr Thomas, a veteran of the US computer industry, said his mandate was to
create an 'autonomous' business unit with global responsibility for
expanding Hyundai's personal computer sales.
Last year, Hyundai sold about Dollars 300m worth of personal computers in
the US. 'We should be able to double that in a few years,' said Mr Thomas.
'We fully expect to have our next generation of desktop and notebook
computers - designed, engineered and assembled in America - shipping to US
and world markets by the end of the year,' he said.
By moving control of its worldwide research &amp; development to the US, Hyundai
will be able to reduce the time it takes to bring a new product to market by
more than 30 per cent, Mr Thomas said.
The relocation will not displace Korean workers, Mr Thomas stressed. Circuit
board manufacturing will continue to be performed at Hyundai's Korean
factories, he said, however, the establishment of a US assembly operation
will enable Hyundai to compete more effectively with US computer makers by
enabling the company to quickly configure systems to customers'
requirements.
A further advantage is that Hyundai will be able to react more rapidly to
price trends, Mr Thomas said. Once the US operation is in full swing  -
probably by year-end - Mr Thomas plans to turn his attention to the European
market and establish European sales, service and assembly operations.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
