<HEADLINE>
FT  21 APR 92 / International Company News in Brief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON and NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COLGATE-Palmolive, the US consumer products group, produced a 25 per cent
increase in first-quarter net income, from Dollars 91.3m last year to
Dollars 113.8m, on sales which rose from Dollars 1.46bn to Dollars Dollars
1.6bn, writes Martin Dickson. Earnings per share rose from 65 cents to 74
cents. The company attributed the profits advance to unit volume growth,
manufacturing efficiencies and a more profitable business mix.
*****
AMERICAN Airlines, the large US carrier which provoked an industry-wide
response when it overhauled its domestic fare structure two weeks ago,
announced yesterday it was reducing fares further in an effort to beat
competitors, writes Nikki Tait. It is converting its 21-day advance fare to
a 14-day advance purchase fare; reducing coach fares in 1,500 domestic
markets and cutting some of the 14-day fares to match competitors'
discounts.
*****
UNITED Technologies, the US aerospace and engineering group, yesterday
reported first-quarter net income of Dollars 109m, or 77 cents a share, up
from Dollars 40m, or 25 cents, in the same period of last year, writes
Martin Dickson. Revenues totalled Dollars 5.2bn, against Dollars 4.8bn.
Contributory factors included the group's restructuring programme and higher
deliveries of aircraft engine spares from its Pratt &amp; Whitney subsidiary.
*****
LOCKHEED, the US defence and aerospace group, made an after-tax profit of
Dollars 66m in the first quarter, up from Dollars 54m a year ago, Nikki Tait
reports.
First-quarter sales were marginally lower at Dollars 2.23bn.
*****
GILLETTE, the Boston-based shaving products group, reported after-tax
profits of Dollars 129.4m in the first three months of 1992, compared with
Dollars 107.2m a year earlier, Nikki Tait reports.
Sales were Dollars 1.21bn, up from Dollars 1.11bn.
</TEXT>
